Apply failing rules to a host. Each rule runs as a four\-phase
atomic transaction; on validation failure, the engine rolls back
to captured pre\-state.

Target options:
  \-H, \-\-host string                    target hostname (required)
  \-u, \-\-user string                    SSH user (default: current user)
  \-k, \-\-key string                     SSH private key path
  \-p, \-\-password string[="<prompt>"]   SSH password (omit value for TTY prompt; reserved literal: <prompt>)
  \-P, \-\-port int                       SSH port (default 22)
      \-\-sudo                           wrap commands in sudo
      \-\-strict\-host\-keys               verify SSH host keys; reject unknown (overrides \-\-no\-strict\-host\-keys)
      \-\-no\-strict\-host\-keys            trust on first use (default today; explicit form for future config\-file override)
  \-C, \-\-capability stringArray         override a detected capability KEY=VALUE; repeatable (e.g. \-C apparmor=true \-C selinux=false). Duplicate KEYs: last value wins.

Rule options:
  \-r, \-\-rules\-dir string         directory to scan for *.yml rule files
      \-\-rule stringArray         load this single rule YAML file (strict — parse errors fail the command); long\-only, repeatable, additive with \-\-rules\-dir and positional *.yml args
  \-s, \-\-severity stringArray     filter rules by severity, repeatable (\-s critical \-s high); choices: critical|high|medium|low
  \-t, \-\-tag stringArray          filter rules by tag, repeatable (\-t pci \-t cis); rules whose tags: array contains any of these match
  \-c, \-\-category string          filter rules by category (\-c access\-control); single value (NOT repeatable like \-s/\-t — later \-c overrides earlier)
  \-f, \-\-framework \-f cis\-rhel9   filter rules to those mapping a control under FRAMEWORK (\-f cis_rhel9). Single value (NOT repeatable like \-s/\-t). Hyphen and underscore are interchangeable: \-f cis\-rhel9 == `\-f cis_rhel9`.
      \-\-control stringArray      filter rules by FRAMEWORK:CONTROL (\-\-control cis\-rhel9:5.1.12); repeatable, OR across values; framework portion accepts hyphen or underscore
  \-x, \-\-var stringArray          override a rule variable, KEY=VALUE; repeatable (e.g. \-x pam_faillock_deny=5). Wins over \-\-config\-dir/defaults.yml. VALUE is spliced literally into rule YAML and may flow into shell commands run by handlers — pass only trusted input.
      \-\-config\-dir string        directory holding defaults.yml (variable defaults source). Phase 3.5 minimum: only defaults.yml is read; per\-host / per\-group / conf.d overrides land in Phase 3.6.

Output options:
      \-\-format string    output format: table or json (deprecated; use \-\-output) (default "table")
  \-o, \-\-output strings   output destination FORMAT[:PATH], repeatable
      \-\-oscal string     write OSCAL Assessment Results to this file (deprecated; use \-\-output oscal:PATH)
  \-q, \-\-quiet            suppress default output (errors still go to stderr)

General:
  \-h, \-\-help   show this help and exit

Examples:
  kensa remediate \-H 192.168.1.211 \-u owadmin \-\-sudo \-r /path/to/rules
  kensa remediate \-H 192.168.1.211 \-s critical \-t pci \-r /path/to/rules
  kensa remediate \-H 192.168.1.211 \-f cis\-rhel9 \-\-control cis_rhel9:5.1.12 \-r /path/to/rules
  kensa remediate \-H web\-01 \-u admin \-\-sudo \-o json \-o oscal:/tmp/results.oscal.json
.fi
.PP
.SS ROLLBACK
.nf
Usage: kensa rollback [MODE] [flags]

Roll back transactions using captured pre\-state. Pick ONE mode:

  \-\-list                  list rollback\-able sessions (read\-only)
  \-\-info SESSION_ID       show session detail (txns + statuses)
  \-\-start SESSION_ID      execute rollback for every committed
                          transaction in the session (needs \-\-host)
  \-\-txn TXN_UUID          legacy: single\-transaction rollback (needs \-\-host)

  \-\-detail                modifier: per\-step breakdown (composes with
                          \-\-list and \-\-info; not \-\-start or \-\-txn)

To find session UUIDs first, run:

  kensa list sessions

Mode (pick one):
      \-\-list           list rollback\-able sessions
      \-\-info string    show detail for SESSION_ID (txns + statuses)
      \-\-start string   execute rollback for every committed txn in SESSION_ID
  \-T, \-\-txn string     legacy: roll back a single transaction by UUID
      \-\-detail         include per\-step breakdown (composes with \-\-list / \-\-info)

Target options (required for \-\-start and \-\-txn):
  \-H, \-\-host string           target hostname (required for \-\-start and \-\-txn)
  \-u, \-\-user string           SSH user (default: current user)
  \-k, \-\-key string            SSH private key path
  \-P, \-\-port int              SSH port (default 22)
      \-\-sudo                  wrap commands in sudo
      \-\-strict\-host\-keys      verify SSH host keys; reject unknown (overrides \-\-no\-strict\-host\-keys)
      \-\-no\-strict\-host\-keys   trust on first use (default today; explicit form for future config\-file override)

Output options:
      \-\-format string   output format: text or json (default "text")
  \-q, \-\-quiet           suppress default output (errors still go to stderr)

General:
  \-h, \-\-help   show this help and exit

Examples:
  kensa rollback \-\-list
  kensa rollback \-\-info 8c3a1e2b\-... \-\-detail
  kensa rollback \-\-start 8c3a1e2b\-... \-H 192.168.1.211 \-u owadmin \-\-sudo
  kensa rollback \-\-txn 9d4b... \-H 192.168.1.211 \-u owadmin \-\-sudo  # legacy
.fi
.PP
.SS HISTORY
.nf
Usage: kensa history [flags]

Query the transaction log. Without filters, lists recent transactions.

Flags:
  \-h, \-\-help               show this help and exit
  \-H, \-\-host string        filter by host ID
  \-R, \-\-rule string        filter by rule ID
  \-S, \-\-since string       filter since duration (e.g. 24h) or RFC3339 time
  \-n, \-\-limit int          maximum rows to return (default 50)
      \-\-format string      output format: table, json, or jsonl (jsonl is transaction\-list only) (default "table")
  \-T, \-\-txn string         get a single transaction by UUID
  \-a, \-\-aggregate string   aggregate key: by_host, by_rule, by_framework_control
      \-\-stats              print summary stats (sessions, transactions, by status / severity / host) and exit
      \-\-prune int          delete sessions and cascade older than N days (destructive; long\-only)
      \-\-force              skip the confirmation prompt for \-\-prune (required in non\-interactive runs)
  \-q, \-\-quiet              suppress default output (errors still go to stderr)

Examples:
  kensa history                                  # 50 most recent
  kensa history \-n 200 \-\-format json             # last 200 as JSON array
  kensa history \-n 200 \-\-format jsonl | jq \-c .  # last 200 as JSON Lines (streamable to log aggregators)
  kensa history \-H 192.168.1.211 \-S 24h          # one host, last 24h
  kensa history \-T 8c3a1e2b\-...                  # one transaction by UUID
  kensa history \-a by_host \-S 7d                 # 7\-day posture per host
  kensa history \-\-prune 30                       # interactive prompt; deletes sessions older than 30 days
  kensa history \-\-prune 30 \-\-force               # non\-interactive (CI / cron); skips the prompt
.fi
.PP
.SS PLAN
.nf
Usage: kensa plan [flags] rule.yml

Preview a rule transaction without executing it. Returns a structured
Plan with captured pre\-state, apply steps, validators, rollback plan,
and warnings.

Flags:
  \-h, \-\-help                           show this help and exit
  \-H, \-\-host string                    target hostname (required)
  \-u, \-\-user string                    SSH user (default: current user)
  \-P, \-\-port int                       SSH port (default 22)
  \-k, \-\-key string                     SSH private key path
  \-p, \-\-password string[="<prompt>"]   SSH password (omit value for TTY prompt; reserved literal: <prompt>)
      \-\-strict\-host\-keys               verify SSH host keys; reject unknown (overrides \-\-no\-strict\-host\-keys)
      \-\-no\-strict\-host\-keys            trust on first use (default today; explicit form for future config\-file override)
      \-\-sudo                           wrap commands in sudo
      \-\-format string                  output format: text, markdown, json, plain (default "text")
  \-q, \-\-quiet                          suppress default output (errors still go to stderr)

Example:
  kensa plan \-H 192.168.1.211 \-u owadmin \-\-sudo \-\-format markdown rule.yml
.fi
